This project focuses on customer segmentation using two popular unsupervised machine learning techniques:

K-Means Clustering (Hard Clustering)
Gaussian Mixture Model (GMM) (Soft Clustering)

The goal is to group customers based on their purchasing behavior and income patterns, helping businesses understand different customer segments for targeted marketing.

Dataset

Dataset Name: Mall Customer Segmentation Dataset
Source: Kaggle
Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/vjchoudhary7/customer-segmentation-tutorial-in-python

Features Used
Annual Income (k$)
Spending Score (1–100)
Age (Optional)
Target Variable
No predefined labels (Unsupervised Learning)
Output: Cluster labels / probabilities
SCENARIO 1 – K-MEANS CLUSTERING
Objective

To group customers into distinct clusters based on similarity using K-Means clustering.

Steps Performed
Imported required libraries:
NumPy
Pandas
Matplotlib
Scikit-learn
Loaded the dataset
Data preprocessing:
Checked and handled missing values
Scaled features using StandardScaler
Selected relevant features:
Annual Income
Spending Score
Determined optimal number of clusters using Elbow Method
Applied K-Means algorithm
Assigned cluster labels to each data point
Visualized clusters using scatter plots
Interpreted cluster characteristics
Evaluation Metrics
Inertia (WCSS – Within Cluster Sum of Squares)
Silhouette Score
Analysis
Observed how different values of K affect clustering
Evaluated compactness and separation of clusters
Identified customer segments such as:
High Income – High Spending
High Income – Low Spending
Low Income – High Spending
Low Income – Low Spending
Studied sensitivity to centroid initialization
Visualizations
Elbow Curve (K vs Inertia)
Cluster Scatter Plot
Cluster Centroids
Key Insights
K-Means creates hard clusters (each point belongs to only one cluster)
Works best for spherical and well-separated clusters
Sensitive to initial centroid selection
SCENARIO 2 – GAUSSIAN MIXTURE MODEL (GMM)
Objective

To cluster customers using probabilistic modeling and capture uncertainty in cluster membership.

Steps Performed
Loaded dataset
Preprocessed data:
Handled missing values
Applied feature scaling
Applied Gaussian Mixture Model (GMM)
Selected number of components (clusters)
Fitted model using Expectation-Maximization (EM) algorithm
Predicted cluster probabilities
Assigned clusters based on highest probability
Compared results with K-Means clustering
Evaluation Metrics
Log-Likelihood
AIC (Akaike Information Criterion)
BIC (Bayesian Information Criterion)
Silhouette Score
Analysis
Compared soft clustering (GMM) vs hard clustering (K-Means)
Observed overlapping clusters
Analyzed cluster shapes:
GMM supports elliptical clusters
K-Means assumes spherical clusters
Evaluated flexibility of GMM over K-Means
Visualizations
Cluster Probability Distribution
GMM Contour Plots
Comparison Plot (K-Means vs GMM)
Key Insights
GMM provides probabilistic clustering
Handles overlapping clusters better than K-Means
More flexible but computationally expensive
Useful when clusters are not clearly separated
